Aug 19 2008 	Not Ready to Recommend	The Chicago O'Hare Garden Hotel offered a *really* great room rate and they aren't that far from O'Hare or the Blue Line train. We didn't need to be close to downtown or North Side, so we thought it'd be a good deal.The hotel is old and a lot of it is run down. The hall carpets are dirty. The walls in the hall are scuffed and need paint. A lot of the fixtures around the hotel are new and very modern, though. It's like we stayed there while they were in the middle of a long, slow upgrade to the property.Our room was a pleasant surprise. It looks like our room had been recently remodeled. The walls were clean and the decor looked fairly new. Our king-size bed was *very* comfortable and the pillows were nice and fluffy. The hotel's van policy is about the best I've ever experienced and their drivers are friendly, helpful and knowledgeable. They'll drive you to and from the airport, to and from the L station nearby, as well as to many nearby facilities, such as the FedEx Kinkos if you need to work.There is no site-wide internet in the hotel. There's no high-speed internet in the rooms, only a very slow WiFi hub in the lobby. There's no business center and working there on the lobby while sitting on one of the sofas is pretty difficult.On checking in, the desk clerk gave us the card key to the room next to ours, which was occupied. A hotel has a basic responsibility to try and ensure that your things are somewhat safe and a mistake like this on check-in does not help me feel like this hotel takes this responsibility seriously.After we'd settled into our room, we noticed that our room smelled like a pet had relieved itself on the carpet.The shower in our room had hot and cold running water -- often at about the same time. The water temp varied greatly while we took showers going quickly from warm to cold to hot.It looks to me like the current owners of this hotel are in the process of making this a nice, little garden hotel, but for me, right now, I think this hotel has quite a bit more to go before I can recommend it, even as a budget or value hotel.	
Aug 17 2008 	Great hotel for the money!	First off, do not use booking.com to book this hotel. Didn't know it, but they are in Europe. Very hard to reach. I used Orbitz (when I found that booking.com really did not have a reservation for us when they said they did) when they had a 20% special and got the room for $60/night.First the good: Hotel staff was very friendly. The room was very clean and nice. It was in a safe neighborhood with a pizza shop across the street, along with Hooters right next door. They also have the Bistro on the first floor, but we did not eat at any of those during our stay. The bed was comfortable and the A/C worked great. Bathroom was clean and the room included a hair dryer and an iron and ironing board was stored in the closet. We got free continental breakfast for the first 2 nights (they did not tell us that it would not be for the entire stay, so you have to ask). The maids did a great job every day cleaning the rooms. There was a 15 minute walk to the blue line that took you into the city, and about a 15 minute walk to the grocery store. The shuttle from the airport was free, however, they do need to replace it. It was comical to see the jalopy coming down to pick us up amongst all the beautiful vans from other hotels. We were there on vacation so we just brushed it off and laughed about it. It took them 25 minutes to get there after we called. But there is a place to sit down in the airport, so we ate breakfast while we waited.Now the bad: Well, the van was in poor shape, but the drivers were very helpful. We stayed on the 2nd floor where it was easier to go up the flight of steps than take the elevator and walk down the hallway. The swimming pool was out of service and they didn't know if it would get fixed. The shower head was great (there were 2), but the temperature of water would flucuate. The lighting in the room was very dim even with all the lights on. They had a fridge in the room, but it was one that you purchased items from instead of allowing you to use it for snacks and such. There were no &quot;do not disturb&quot; signs so the maid came to the room daily (we are the few that don't like that service), but they did a great job cleaning. If you like ESPN, then this is the hotel for you. There are like 4 channels of ESPN, so we found it hard to find something to watch at night. USA was our choice. Free HBO too, but the movies playing stunk. But of course that was not the hotels' fault at all though.I would definitely stay there again. For the money, this was a great little hotel with the things we were looking for. Hopefully they will put some money into the pool and get it open. NOTES ON THE CITY: MUST DO: If you didn't drive, GET A CTA pass!! It was our best friend during our stay. It takes you on all the &quot;L&quot; trains, and the busses. The city is easy to get around if you have a map. But be prepared to walk and wait for traffic to cross at all the crossings. Lot's of bicyclists, pedestrians, taxis and busses. Figure about $15 per person for each meal. Take a speedboat or agricultural tour on the SeaDog (I actually purchased a buy one / get one on Ebay). Shop the Magnificent Mile. Go to the zoo in Lincoln Park for FREE. See the Chicago Cultural center for FREE. Millenium Park is FREE (concerts there too) There are many FREE things to do. Google &quot;Free Things to do in Chicago&quot;. You will be amazed.We loved the Chicago style hotdog ($4 each), but not too thrilled on the deep dish (sorry Chicago, but our pizzas are better). Plus you pay $18 for a small deep dish (feeds 2 people). Our best meal (and cheapest) came from a small Italian restaruant near Randolph Street. The meal came with bread, salad and a pasta dish all for $22. That's for 2 of us. OH YEA... CHICAGO TAXES EVERYTHING. UP TO 13.25% on clothing. OUCH!!! Have a great stay. We did!!	
